title: For Sale:  AR-15 in 300 BLACKOUT
postcontent:
New flat-top AR-15 chambered in 300 BLACKOUT, has only has 10 rounds fired through it for test purposes. Stainless steel barrel with 1/8 twist, black custom flush-fit flash suppressor, quadrail and two-rail gas block, has custom 2-sided laser etched dust cover with two official 300 blackout logos and the blood-spatter logo from the movie "300." Comes with one Lancer Advanced Warfighter Magazine, and will also include 50 rounds of 147 Gr rounds of new brass 300 BLK stamped PNW ammo. $1100, FTF in Knoxville preferred, will ship in state without the ammo. Will make a great hunting rifle! Uses standard 5.56 magazines and BCGs.

Here are some specs and other info on 300 Blackout:
This system was developed to launch 30 caliber projectiles from the AR platform without a reduction in magazine capacity and compatible with the standard bolt.

Full power 115-125 grain ammunition matches the ballistics of the 7.62x39mm AK, and eclipses 5.56mm with much higher-mass projectiles for a more dramatic effect on the target. Or choose subsonic cartridges for optimal use with a sound suppressor - 220 grain Sierra OTM (open-tip match) bullets vastly outperforms a 9mm MP5-SD in penetration and long range accuracy.

Ammo and brass prices are low - Remington 115 grain UMC ammo is $12.99 a box MSRP - and it is not bare bones. It has waterproofed primers, crimped and cannelured open-tip match bullets, and a low-drag design.

At 300 meters, 300 BLK has 16.7% more energy than 7.62x39mm. Max effective range, using M4 military standards for hit probability, is 440 meters for a 9 inch barrel, and 460 meters for a 16 inch barrel. 300 BLK from a 9 inch barrel has the same energy at the muzzle as a 14.5 inch barrel M4, and about 5% more energy at 440 meters - even though the barrel is much shorter.

For hunting - think of it as like a 30-30 but from an AR. After you are done, you can remove your 5-round magazine and put in a 30 for plinking or home defense. For ammo, Remington has you covered with the Premiere AccuTip 125 grain. Want industry-wide support? Over 60 companies have already announced or sell products.

Due to the high efficiency of the cartridge, less powder is used than 5.56mm, which results in a rifle that is a comfortable to shoot - even with a short barrel.

Reloading dies available from Forster products, Reamers and headspace guages available from Pacific Tool and Gauge.

DESIGN OBJECTIVES
• Create a reliable compact 30-cal solution for the AR platform
• Utilize existing inventory magazines while retaining their full capacity
• Create the optimal platform for sound and flash suppressed fire
• Create compatible supersonic ammo that matches 7.62x39 ballistics
• Provide the ability to penetrate barriers with high-mass projectiles
• Provide all capabilities in a lightweight, durable, low recoiling package

REASONS 7.62x39 WAS NOT CONSIDERED
Extreme cartridge taper
• Reduces reliability of feeding in AR Magazines
• Reduces Magazine capacity
• Cartridge taper induces considerably higher bolt thrust-
exacerbating the AR Bolt's weaknesses
• Requires a larger Bolt Face which reduces Bolt Locking Lug strength-
exacerbating the AR Bolt's weaknesses
Limited projectile selection
• 0.311" diameter not a common option in most modern bullets

title: For Sale:  Ruger 10/22 mildot scope,polished bolt, sling, box CCI Stingers
postcontent:
I am also including 1 full box of CCI Stinger ammo.

I have a Ruger 10/22 that I bought new and planned on turning into a target rifle but plans and priorities have changed. It started out as a maple stock plain 10/22 when I got it. I have since trued and polished all the friction surfaces of the bolt and removed the overspray paint from the bearing surfaces in the receiver. The bolt now rides way smoother than it originally did, the action feels a lot smoother. I also installed swivel studs for a sling and the rifle will come with the sling pictured. I also installed a 2x7 power illuminated mildot scope which fits the rifle nicely.

One thing I hate about 10/22s is the absence of a cleaning rod hole in the receiver. I like to clean rifles from the chamber to the muzzle so I took the receiver to my fathers machine shop and drilled a hole for a cleaning rod. It lines up perfectly with the barrel and looks factory.

The bolt lock function of the rifle was left alone, I did not do the bolt lock release mod simply because I only use the bolt lock to transport the rifle and didn't want the bolt going closed in my car while transporting it and have storm troopers pull me over and arrest me.

All in all its a nice rifle that has been fully gone through and tweaked. You can buy one of these new for 220 plus around 15 for tax and I have another 60 in the scope and 20 in the sling plus my time polishing the bolt and drilling a hole for a cleaning rod so 220 is a reasonable price for someone that wants a scoped 10/22 with some basic mods already done. It has fired approx 300 rounds and killed 1 skunk since I bought it and has been cleaned after shooting every range session and hunt. 


I will not ship, no trades, and will only deal ftf with people from Ohio only with a state id.

I have a 1943 Russian Mosin Nagant 91/30 rifle, WW2 era, fires 7.62x54r.
All original, comes with all the goods:
Bayonet, tool kit, oil can, leather clip pouches, etc.
This rifle has a very nice bore, also wood is in great shape, still has it's veneer, has not been stripped.  Everything except the bolt is still coated in cosmoline. Round receiver models with this scallop are the better shooters.  Super clean and nice for being a WW2 era weapon.  $200 cash.  I am located in Denver near city park.
